SIMPLE: heap
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Heap
<hw>Heap</hw> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>heep</ets>, <ets>heap</ets>, heap, multitude, AS.
<ets>he⟦aacute⟧p</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>h⟦omac⟧p</ets>, D.
<ets>hoop</ets>, OHG. <ets>houf</ets>, <ets>h⟦umac⟧fo</ets>, G.
<ets>haufe</ets>, <ets>haufen</ets>, Sw. <ets>hop</ets>, Dan.
<ets>hob</ets>, Icel. <ets>h⟦omac⟧pr</ets> troop, flock, Russ.
<ets>kupa</ets> heap, crowd, Lith. <ets>kaupas</ets>. Cf. <er>Hope</er>,
in <ets>Forlorn hope</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A crowd; a throng; a
multitude or great number of persons.</def> <mark>[Now Low or
Humorous]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wisdom of a <qex>heap</qex> of learned men.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>heap</qex> of vassals and slaves.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had <qex>heaps</qex> of friends.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A great number or large quantity of things not
placed in a pile; <as>as, a <ex>heap</ex> of trouble</as>.</def>
<mark>[Now Low or Humorous]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A vast <qex>heap</qex>, both of places of scripture and
quotations.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Burnet.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have noticed a <qex>heap</qex> of things in my life.</q>
<rj><qau>R. L. Stevenson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pile or mass; a collection of things laid in a
body, or thrown together so as to form an elevation; <as>as, a
<ex>heap</ex> of earth or stones</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Huge <qex>heaps</qex> of slain around the body rise.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj></p>

<p><-- (Computer programming) The main segment of memory available for
dynamic assignment -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Heap
<hw>Heap</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Heaped</conjf> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧pt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Heaping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>he⟦aacute⟧pian</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To collect in great
quantity; to amass; to lay up; to accumulate; -- usually with
<xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>heap</ex> up treasures</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though he <qex>heap</qex> up silver as the dust.</q> <rj><qau>Job.
xxvii. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To throw or lay in a heap; to make a heap of; to
pile; <as>as, to <ex>heap</ex> stones</as>; -- often with
<ptcl>up</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>heap</ex> up earth</as>; or with
<ptcl>on</ptcl>; <as>as, to <ex>heap</ex> on wood or
coal</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 678 pr=JMD --></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To form or round into a heap, as in measuring; to
fill (a measure) more than even full.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Heaper</ent>⟦br⟧
